Rectal adenocarcinoma, status-post primary resection and liver resection.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Thomas is a very pleasant 81-year-old male from Indiana Independence.  He is an established patient of Dr. Ashley Lee Brown's.  I was asked to see him for postoperative education purposes.
1.  May 2010 - presented locally with abdominal discomfort.  Subsequent colonoscopy performed showing a 6.0-cm x 4.0-cm rectal mass.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.  PET/CT-scan showing FDG uptake in a right lower lung nodule, the primary rectal mass, and two liver lesions.
2.  June 2010 - right pulmonary lesion biopsies confirmed metastatic adenocarcinoma with a colorectal primary.
3.  June through July 2010 - received concurrent chemotherapy with infusional 5-FU and radiation.  Overall tolerated well.
4.  October 2010 - seen by Dr. Brown of Medical Oncology, Dr. Chris Gillespie of Thoracic Surgery, Dr. Felix of Colorectal Surgery, and Dr. Powell of General Surgery with the joint consensus to proceed with resection of the primary rectal cancer and the liver lesions with subsequent resection of the lung nodule at a later date.
5.  October 29, 2010 - underwent low-anterior resection with temporary diverting loop ileostomy and left hepatectomy by Drs. Felix and Powell.  Surgical pathology from the colorectal resection noting grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 2.0-cm x 1.2-cm x 0.5-cm mass in the rectum invading into the muscularis propria.  The tumor extended to within 1.5-cm of the radial resection margins.  Negative surgical margins, and 6 of 22 regional lymph nodes were positive for metastatic carcinoma.  Liver wedge resection of II, III, and IV consistent with metastatic adenocarcinoma forming a 3.0-cm x 2.8-cm x 2.4-cm mass with negative surgical margins by 0.5-cm.  Wedge resection of liver Segment V consistent with metastatic colon adenocarcinoma forming a 2.4-cm x 2.0-cm x 1.6-cm mass present at the surgical resection margin.  Staged at a T2, N2, M1.
Mr. Thomas is currently in the ICU having been admitted after an episode of atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response and hypotension requiring transfusion.  He is overall stable and doing well.

